The disparity lies in one last key variable: the amount of financial aid that schools give out.

Rather than being listed as an expense, financial aid is subtracted from each school's revenue in financial reporting. Thus, while total revenue growth has [matched spending growth at each 5C school](#appendix), net student revenue has not, and even decreased in 2019-20.

**Financial aid, meanwhile, has grown at a greater rate than tuition** at CMC, Pomona and Pitzer, and just under the rate of tuition growth at Scripps.

[ReLineChart fields:`["tuition", "finaid"]` isCum:`true` isTwoFields:`true`/]

All 5C schools cover 100% of demonstrated need, according to the schools’ financial aid websites. For students who receive need-based financial aid, who made up between 38% of the student population at Pitzer to 54% at Pomona in 2019-20, the average **cost of attendance after aid has not increased by nearly as much as tuition.** (phrase that better)

